## Methods {#sec-methods}

**Data.** {% if ctx.primary_dataset %}{% set dd = ctx.primary_dataset.definition|clean %}The analysis substrate is {{ (dd[0]|lower) ~ dd[1:] }}{% if ctx.primary_dataset.source %} ({{ ctx.primary_dataset.source|clean }}){% endif %}.{% endif %} Provenance was traced to {{ ctx.provenance|length }} candidate source publications, of which {{ ctx.acquired }} {{ 'was' if ctx.acquired == 1 else 'were' }} acquired (see References).

**Agents.** The investigation ran a fixed pipeline of Asta agents (summarized above).{% if 'AutoDiscovery' in ctx.agents_used %} Asta's **AutoDiscovery** proposed candidate relationships and ranked them by a surprise signal.{% endif %}{% if 'DataVoyager' in ctx.agents_used %} Each prespecified statistical test was executed by Asta's **DataVoyager**, an automated analysis agent.{% endif %}{% if 'Theorizer' in ctx.agents_used %} Theories were generated by Asta's literature-grounded **Theorizer** under accuracy- and novelty-focused objectives.{% endif %}{% if 'Paper Finder' in ctx.agents_used %} Source publications were located with Asta's **Paper Finder** over Semantic Scholar.{% endif %}

**Reproduction protocol.** For every candidate law we committed a prespecified test — statistic, decision metric, and success threshold — *before* analysis, re-ran it on the in-hand dataset, and challenged the result with a negative-control audit (the predictor shuffled, or an equivalent) before the verdict stood. Verdicts are two-axis: an *outcome* (held / partial / failed / n-a) crossed with *testability* (tested / proxy-only / untestable).

**Theory verification.** Generated theories were triaged for testability against the data in hand; only theories with a prespecified, runnable test were verified, under the same analyze-then-audit protocol.
